snippet.textDisplay:
Problem is - WHO shall pay it and HOW ? Paid leave is effectively expensive insurance, calculated as every other - based on overbooking and statistics. They work only when small fraction of population make use of them at any given time. Current situation is different and paid sick leave is NOT the instrument you need.

Also: for small businesses it is not about sick leave - because even NOT paying anything doesn't solve basic problem: work NOT being done.

snippet.textDisplay:
Im from the UK its not as black and white as your making out. So long as your a "Permenant Full TIme" employee, you get it. Zero hours contract employees get it as long as they earn over a certain amount. So that screws over a large amount of people. Also the self employed, sole traders, etc don't get it.
So saying the UK gives all its workers sick pay as a blanket term just isn't true.

Even with the latest 'Ferlow' measures for people who can't work due to the pandemic, there are lots of exceptions.

So yea, better than the US situation but we're still along way from being perfect.

snippet.textDisplay: New Zealand sick leave isnt that great though you've got to work for an employer for 6 months and you only get 5 days which yes can roll over to a maximum of 20days, which isnt very useful if you get sick for more than those five days and yes we have acc but that's there if you get really sick or injured. I've been working at my local supermarket for a year and a half and the supermarket was bought by a new owner so a new contract and new employer, right at the time my sick leave rolled over for the year so I more than likely dont have sick leave and wont have it till august despite working for a year and half not changing jobs. Like yeah they bought out my annual leave no idea about sick leave. So not the holly grail, they can choose to pay me sick leave before the 6months but it would still come out of the 5 you get after 6months then yearly. So still better than America but still not that great cause as I found out 5days doesnt go very far especially for my coworkers with kids who use it when their kids are sick and then have none left for them and come back too soon because your acutely aware of how much you've used and try to save it for the rest of the year even though you're still partially sick.
